muKern ROADMAP
==============

muKern is built in milestones. Each one is small, self-contained, and
leaves a kernel that still boots and runs on all three architectures.

DONE
----

M0  Boot on three arches.
    x86_64 (Multiboot -> long mode), arm64 (QEMU virt, EL1), riscv64
    (OpenSBI -> S-mode). One UART per arch brought up by hand.

M1  Traps / exceptions.
    IDT on x86_64, VBAR_EL1 on arm64, stvec on riscv64. A synchronous
    fault dumps registers and panics instead of triple-faulting. The
    shell's `fault` command exercises this.

M2  Tasks & cooperative scheduler.
    Fixed table of tasks, each with its own stack and saved context.
    Per-arch context switch (arch/<arch>/switch.S + ctx.c). Round-robin
    pick with a never-blocking idle task so the run queue is never empty.

M3  Synchronous IPC.
    send / recv / call / reply. Blocking rendezvous, no kernel-side
    buffering (the L4 discipline). Fixed-size messages: a few words plus
    an optional (ptr,len). call/reply give RPC; the server loop is just
    recv -> handle -> reply.

M4  Driver servers.
    The UART driver becomes a task (kernel/srv/serial.c) that owns the
    port and speaks the con.h protocol. The kernel core stops touching
    devices entirely (only the boot banner and panic still write the UART
    directly, because they must work without the scheduler).

M5  Console multiplexer, init, and shell-as-task.
    A console server (kernel/srv/console.c) fans one client stream out to
    every device. The init/root task (kernel/core/init.c) starts the
    servers, publishes their endpoints, and launches the shell. The shell
    (kernel/core/repl.c) is now a plain client task that knows only con.h.

M6  VGA text driver (x86_64).
    arch/x86_64/vga.c drives the 80x25 buffer at 0xB8000; kernel/srv/vga.c
    wraps it as a con.h server. The console server now writes to serial
    AND screen, so the shell demos on a real display (docs/vga-demo.png).

M7  PS/2 keyboard & input multiplexing -- a real local console (x86_64).
    arch/x86_64/kbd.c polls the i8042 and translates scan-code set 1 to
    ASCII (shift + caps); kernel/srv/kbd.c wraps it as a con.h server. Input
    can now come from the serial line OR the keyboard: the console server
    gained a non-blocking CON_POLL op and watches every input source in a
    yield loop, so the same shell is driven from a serial terminal and a
    local keyboard at once (type on the keyboard, see it on the VGA screen --
    docs/vga-keyboard-demo.png). No serial line required.

NEXT
----

M8  Address-space isolation & user mode.
    Give each task its own page tables and run servers/shell in user mode
    (ring 3 / EL0 / U-mode). IPC becomes a real syscall trap and the
    kernel copies message buffers across the protection boundary -- the
    con.h protocol does not change, only the plumbing beneath it. This is
    the step that turns "microkernel by structure" into "microkernel with
    enforced isolation".

M9  Preemptive scheduling.
    Per-arch timer interrupt (LAPIC / generic timer / CLINT) drives a time
    slice so a buggy task can no longer hog the CPU. Cooperative yield
    stays as a fast path. This also enables interrupt-driven input, so the
    serial and keyboard servers can block on an IRQ instead of polling.

M10 Capabilities / typed endpoints.
    Replace the flat svc_* registry with per-task capability slots so a
    task can only message endpoints it was explicitly granted -- the seL4
    style of authority.

Later: a memory-server task for dynamic allocation, and a second
filesystem/block server to prove the model scales past console I/O.

